{"cursor":"5685","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Pitting corrosion', or 'pitting', is a form of extremely localized corrosion\nthat leads to the creation of small holes in the metal. The driving power for\npitting corrosion is the depassivation of a small area, which becomes anodic\nwhile an unknown but potentially vast area becomes cathodic, leading to very\nlocalized galvanic corrosion. The corrosion penetrates the mass of the metal,\nwith limited diffusion of ions. The mechanism of pitting corrosion is probably\nthe same as crevice corrosion.\n","linknr":156,"url":"Pitting_corrosion","recorded":1362481556,"links":22,"instances":["chemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Corrosion","Fouling"],"headings":["Mechanism","Susceptible alloys","Environment","Examples","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Fe_corrosion.PNG/220px-Fe_corrosion.PNG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Corrosion.Pit.jpg/220px-Corrosion.Pit.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Silver_Bridge_collapsed%2C_Ohio_side.jpg/220px-Silver_Bridge_collapsed%2C_Ohio_side.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["passivation","chemistry"]],"members":["passivation"],"related":["Corrosion","Anode","Cathode","Galvanic_corrosion","Crevice_corrosion","Passivation_(chemistry)","Stainless_steel","Nickel_alloys","Aluminum_alloy","Molybdenum","Chloride","Sea_water","Autocatalytic","Ion","Thiosulfate","Fluoride","Iodide","Sulfide","Oil_well","Kraft_paper","Methionine","Lysine","Co